3
00:00:09,450 --> 00:00:14,060
Once you have estimated a VAR, EViews provides a number of useful tools

4
00:00:14,060 --> 00:00:18,250
that allow you to improve the specification of the model.

5
00:00:18,250 --> 00:00:23,470
As mentioned previously, EViews allows you to check the stability of the VAR

6
00:00:23,470 --> 00:00:26,970
by providing the inverse roots of the characteristic AR

7
00:00:26,970 --> 00:00:31,920
polynomial, both in table and graph.

8
00:00:31,920 --> 00:00:40,020
The estimated VAR is stationary if all the roots lie inside the unit circle.

9
00:00:40,020 --> 00:00:50,440
So from the VAR window why not go into "View, Lag Structure,"

10
00:00:50,440 --> 00:00:55,520
and one has the option to select "AR Roots Table" or "Graph."

11
00:00:55,520 --> 00:00:58,270
Let's select Graph.

12
00:00:58,270 --> 00:01:05,890
And here we see the inverse roots of the characteristic polynomial.

13
00:01:05,890 --> 00:01:12,290
And we can see that they are all inside the unit circle, including this one.

14
00:01:12,290 --> 00:01:18,220
Which means that this particular VAR stationary since all roots

15
00:01:18,220 --> 00:01:21,250
lie inside the unit circle.

16
00:01:21,250 --> 00:01:26,010
So this is important because if the VAR is not stable,

17
00:01:26,010 --> 00:01:31,760
certain results such as impulse response standard errors are not valid.

18
00:01:31,760 --> 00:01:41,250
So if the solution to the characteristic polynomial has a root for l equal to 1,

19
00:01:41,250 --> 00:01:47,470
then it means that either some or all of the variables in the VAR process

20
00:01:47,470 --> 00:01:50,790
are integrated of order 1.

21
00:01:50,790 --> 00:01:54,480
It may be also the case that the cointegration between the variables

22
00:01:54,480 --> 00:01:55,410
exists.

23
00:01:55,410 --> 00:01:59,440
And this instance would be better analyzed in the context of the vector error

24
00:01:59,440 --> 00:02:01,480
collection model (VECM).

25
00:02:01,480 --> 00:02:09,820
